The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", according to a leaflet
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually of advanced age, cannot work, for example, for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who “return” to witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
"Men seldom suffer such but."
“Healthy young women are not isolated either, because they help in the labors and have children,” explains a nun who, in the capital of the West African state Burkina Faso, takes care of a special residence of more than a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual “social measure”.
He issued an information leaflet that should help prevent witch hunts.
However, this has a drawback.
“More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read,” warns the newspaper Die Standard about the disadvantages of written awareness.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, neighboring Burkina Faso, last week Ammy Hemmah, 72, died when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate cluster of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman stuck in the oil that is used for ritual anointing.
It caught on fire when the group wanted to "expel evil spirits" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all educational levels.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso: “Human soul eaters have always been a danger,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to appease the witch hunt, in Gambia last year the president still participated in it.
“Gambian President Jammeh, after the death of his aunt, launched a wide-ranging witch hunt that allegedly had been linked to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself through black magic.”
“To help him, he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president’s personal escort, forcibly took randomly chosen men and women from among the Gambian peoples to the president’s property in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
On the estate, the arrested people had to drink a pot of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that, in addition, caused them intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of those arrested did not survive the stay on the estate.
After international pressure, they finally released about a thousand people.
Bakala tenant: warms up with charcoal stoves and signs higher rent
The man, old and old, crossed the doors of the customer service center of the company RPG Byty of the "coal magnate" Zdexek Bakala, the largest private owner of flats for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he was carrying documents with the new three-story rental contracts: his, his daughter’s and his son’s, who is serving sentence.
All three of them have just taken advantage of the rent liberalization.
Instead of 3,500 Czech kronor per month, the child will pay from next year 4,100 kronor for a two-room flat with a separate second-class kitchen.
"Furthermore, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man shows with his finger in the new contract of his son, over whose signature he has full powers.
“But I signed it,” he explains half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which called the new rental conditions "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants do not sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, when it will publish a guide informing how to proceed in these cases.
But, in this case, the man only makes one move.
“Everyone says something,” he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a major testing laboratory for liberalization.
After the New Year it will happen with the vast majority of the flats that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rental.
That’s why Aktuáln.cz decided to visit the “laboratory” in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of the four of Ostrava and, on Tuesday at nine o’clock, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and beside them a machine to pick up the number.
"Rent 2011", can be read on a light button of your touch screen.
When you press it, a little paper with a number comes out of the machine.
It hardly gives time to read "157" and already the number appears on the big screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in the queue.
Soon after, an elderly couple arrives to ask, but the crowd in the room is not here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve common problems, as in the past: requests for settlements, insurance issues, and the like.
Letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava at the tenants’ mailboxes for most of the 44,000 RPG-owned flats around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes a rental increase of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18, a special window opens in the customer service center for new rentals.
“It’s been working for a week, so it’s starting,” respond, after briefly doubting, the workers who are in it when the client presents himself as a journalist.
Liberalization and Bakala’s old mining floors are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, they were treated loud and clear by the vice-president of parliament, Lubomír Zaorálek, of the SSD, and now appear continuously in the newspapers of the area.
"Twenty years later I want a new floor."
“Neither did I change the damn bathroom dish,” the man mentioned in the introduction vents.
According to the workers, for the time being, retirees come to check if they receive a discount on rent if they sign on time, as promised by the special offer of RPG.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract by December 15 will also receive half of the February rental discount.
However, the window of mining “liberalization” certainly fails to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
“Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, only about forty or fifty people were asked about the rental in 2011,” she said.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on the rent, an independent judge will have to settle the matter.
“This is not a threat, but information about the only way to proceed and completely in accordance with the law,” RPG warns on its pages.
“You’re not going to judge anyone here,” says one of the Byty RPG employees, and a man standing on the street in front of the customer service center gives her, at least in part, the reason.
“I get a 13,000 pension and I have 5,000 left for food; I don’t have the means to go to court,” he says.
But immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see."
“Mr. Zaorálek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people wait,” he says.
Rental regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic in early 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
“Current rents still don’t cover even the amounts needed to maintain the community fund,” recalls Pavel Klima, director of RPG Byty’s residential portfolio, adding that the careless state of the community fund that angers tenants is, for landlords, the main reason to increase rent.
While during the five years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest four billion in apartments, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen that hangs from the ceiling, in front of the seats in the waiting room, now repeats some data that highlights in red.
"The increase in rent in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG properties."
“In addition, there will always be a maximum of 7.50 Czech kronor per square meter,” it says on the screen.
Only increase by 38% the rent of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio.
“In such cases, it is an increase from extremely low amounts of 19.66 kronor per square meter,” RPG says.
On 2,600 floors, the rental will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that the liberalization will not affect rents suddenly, but will escalate between four to eight years.
In addition, it adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rise of the rent (see the graph) again on the floors, mainly in heating savings: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to those who sign the lease hike agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need childcare
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would say that it also hides inside a small nursery with everything appropriate to such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October of last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can come to it.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from which many well-known buildings from Brno came out, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-kindergarten.
About 90 people work at the company, mainly in the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, the nursery is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers to its workers as part of its social program.
Constructors and architects in this way have the possibility of combining a demanding profession with the care of children.
The mini-kindergarten was an idea of the Arch.Designu employees themselves and, with the support of management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company’s mini-kindergarten is financed through the European Social Fund under the Human Resources and Employment Operational Programme, as well as the Czech Republic’s state budget.
Thanks to the funding provided (more than 2.8 million CZK) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When funding runs out (two years), Arch.Design is required to keep the mini-kindergarten running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the company Economy Rating contributed to the submission of the funding request.
The care of the children is in the hands of qualified staff; in addition, a nurse and a teacher of the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care. The nursery currently welcomes children without age limit, although most of them are under three years old.
Since it is a "mini-child care", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with the shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to suit the needs of parents and the children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is an individual teaching and care, the contents of the mini-kindergarten program are comparable to the usual preschool education program.
In it children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to preparation for school, they teach to English.
The class not only has toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself create a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up children late from school when away from their workplace.
Parents are more productive as they work.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the firms that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened the marketing of personnel.
The House of Bones continues to fascinate after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the column of a dinosaur, and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Due to its skeleton-like shape, the locals nicknamed it "the house of bones."
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a façade reminiscent of the scales and the omnipresent lines gently curved, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with dream lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, you observe a certain geometry, rhythm and carefully thought out order.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Snake and the twisting of the shapes continues to surprise us also inside.
Corrugated wood copies window frames, railings, door ornaments, mirrors, and signs.
Casa Batlló, which is located in the Eixample neighborhood at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gràcia, emerged from the refurbishment of a house from the year 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí’s idea of carrying out a novel and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, made up of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated on the design.
In fact, in their project plans arose ornaments for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in Casa Batlló’s proposals was the beginning of Jujol’s successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Casa Milá and Gaudí’s Park Güell, where other pieces of it are found.
Due to its organic shape, the locals shortly after its completion nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of yawning".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia, appears.
Other sculptural elements of the building hide religious motifs.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the time of central heating with vents and typical fireplaces.
It can be strange its inclination of forty-five degrees.
During construction, Gaudí did not respect the building rules of the moment and did not allow himself to be influenced by them.
Still, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although evidently in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, after its completion, the town hall was so impacted with the result that it requested that it be corrected.
It bothered him, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, on the contrary: just fifteen days after the request of the town hall, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor were the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The house, six floors, is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted in breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of the connection of space.
The common part can be completely connected by opening the doors of the lounges and a larger group can communicate in this way without any hassle, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only got a new façade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles covering the inner courtyard and skylights.
The game with the two colors provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb the sun’s rays.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most recharged apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the famous creator’s birth.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and they expanded visits to the common area and the loft, including the roof terrace.
The price of the entrance to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of entry to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
