How to choose the mattress and the socks: women and men look for different things
Nothing of a pompous frame for the bed; what really gives its quality to a good bed is the surface for lying down, that is, the mattress and the basement.
First of all, they must be complemented perfectly so that they adapt to the specific users.
During the selection come into play numerous items including the weight, height, health and sex of the owner.
It is also important the type of interior in which the mattress and the basement are located.
A typical example?
For example, in a weekend cottage that doesn’t usually have heating, latex mattresses should not be used because they “heat” more slowly.
In addition, they usually weigh considerably more than the usual polyurethane mattresses.
Therefore, it is necessary to turn them around more often.
If the center channels are not properly aerated and, above, are on a firm basis, they keep moisture inside.
When it comes to choosing a bed, habits also influence.
Those who have spent a lot of time abroad often use a very high mattress with a soft layer and will have trouble feeling good on a lower, harder surface.
“Almost all the hockey players who came back from the NHL complained that they didn’t sleep as well here.”
"For their crushed shoulders, heels and hips they needed mattresses with a soft layer of viscoelastic."
"These types of mattresses are also recommended for people with diabetes who have time problems with the nervous system, so they receive bad information from the joints and skin," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in padded furniture.
Many hockey players, like other clients, have long preferred viscoelastic mattresses.
"Today there is no problem, because they have these suitable Tempur and Magniflex Italians, but also the Czech brand Tropico."
You no longer have to be an NHL player to appreciate the viscoelastic.
This “miracle” works in a very simple way.
Optimizes your stiffness and shape depending on the heat absorbed or adapts to your body heat.
Nothing exerts pressure; during the night, it will not spin like after a hard match.
It just sleeps better.
Viscoelastic also works as a protection against sores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add to its height the length of its feet, that is, between 21 and 34 cm.
A man or woman with a height of about 180 cm will need a bed between 210 and 220 cm.
The minimum width for a person should be, in a double room, 90 cm, in total 180 cm.
In the case of single rooms, for example single rooms, it is recommended at least between 120 and 140 cm.
So that a possible visit is also comfortable.
"If not, you can apply a simple rule to calculate the width: when lying face up, you should have your hands comfortably shrunken towards the elbows," advises the engineer Helena Prokopová, an expert of Cechu ?alouník? to decoratér, who has been dealing with the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture, a subject that specializes in schools.
In double rooms, each needs its own pillow and mattress, so during the purchase you have to pay attention to combine the height of the mattresses.
Otherwise, it will be necessary to mount the baseboards at different heights, which is not always possible in all beds.
Foam mattresses should have a minimum height of 14 cm, models with spring interior a minimum of 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters are for the layer that adapts to the shapes and softens.
“When you touch it with your hand or when you sit on the mattress, you certainly shouldn’t notice the springs,” warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a certain type of mattress.
Fully padded bedrooms, in which the mattress and base are like Siamese, make no sense in the bedroom.
Mattresses breathe badly and you can’t wash their case, which is often done today.
And, since we sweat between 0.2 and 0.75 liters of sweat each night, it is clear that after about five or seven years the mattress will begin to remind us of a large (and congested) screen.
For this reason, specialists reject slogans that speak of a mattress life of up to 25 years or even a lifetime warranty.
However, everything has a but.
Therefore, the sellers give a tip: on mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, take care of cleaning and washing the cover, but better add a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Although mattress covers with zip closure are currently manufactured throughout their perimeter, so when they are opened they are left in two parts (something very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), their handling in larger models (and by a single person) when lifting the mattress can seem like a fight between a fly weight and a heavy weight.
In bed, instead of a broomstick, do you have a firm board?
Never!
As much as for the beds designed to spend one night the visits.
However, you should make (if you do not already have them) ventilation holes on the table and you should use it with a mattress with springs on the inside and a minimum height of 15 cm with the springs in bags (such as the German Taschenfederkern) and a soft layer.
Polyurethane mattresses should not be used on such bases.
For non-articulate sheet beds containing between 14 and 18 sheets, latex mattresses or sandwich mattresses (e.g., a combination of latex and coconut fiber) can be used, although it is always better to have a bed bed with a higher number of sheets, 28 or more, in which the sheets of the lumbar zone are reinforced and their rigidity can be adjusted.
Articulable sheet pads should not be used with a spring mattress, as it does not react to recline.
In addition to adjusting the rigidity of the sheets, shoulder protection can also be used.
This is a special fixation of the sheets that allows you to press or even tilt the sheets in such a way that they "round" the shoulders perfectly during sleep.
For men who have very wide shoulders, this is very important.
Even the manufacturers of mattresses remember them, who, in the "males", began to use a softer area precisely around the shoulders.
They also remember women, for whom they put a softer area around the hips.
For the most demanding customers, there are pads with cross or tablet structure with the so-called multitorsion damping.
The pressure is distributed between different points and the tension is lowered.
You should also keep in mind that, even if you use the right mattress and basement, if you use a bad (big and "soft") pillow, most of the advantages will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should hold the head and the corners can only reach the shoulders, so that the muscles of the same can relax.
The recommended suitable size is 50 x 60 cm, something normal for example in Scandinavia.
When lying on your side, the pillow should be on the same level (when combined with the shoulder backing or the softer area of the mattress) as the height of the shoulders.
Modern mattresses have something to do, it seems, with the original straw-filled mattresses.
Manufacturers continue to use, more and more often, natural materials or, at least, mixtures.
In fact, biological mattresses are in fashion.
Petroleum-based raw materials, with which polyurethane foam is manufactured, are filled with natural oils, for example castor or soybean.
In fact, virtually every known manufacturer uses soybeans.
"Biological, in the case of mattresses, means that the center is made only of materials of natural origin," explains Petr Va?ek of the company Tropico Plus.
Also, natural substances are used during the manufacture of the mattress cover, one of the first aloe vera.
But you can also opt for microcapsules, which release a fresh aroma to forest or lavender.
There are also differences for men and women.
While men "cool" with vegetable extracts of breeze, so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and cools the body, women prefer to "heat" the cover.
The red pepper extract improves blood circulation, so that women feel more warmth.
Favorites currently?
Mattresses made of cold foam, which are more porous, with an adapted cell structure, which makes them more permeable than those of normal polyurethane and offer more permeability.
The combination of various cold and viscoelastic foam stiffnesses make it possible to manufacture mattresses from various zones that know perfectly where the head, shoulders and heels go.
A good quality mattress will cost you 7,000 crowns up.
Those who perform a therapeutic function usually have a lower VAT, since they are considered as a means of health.
The first to gain this advantage in the Czech Republic was Gumotex.
It is difficult to save on mattresses and footbeds.
Sometimes you can approve offers from manufacturers or sellers, who sometimes offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers Duofreeze mattresses with a memory foam attached to the case for 11,990 crowns.
The second one is free.
The era of viscoelastics with an open cell structure and high density began with the "cosmic" material of Tempur.
It initially emerged as material for NASA, because during takeoffs the astronauts were subjected to a huge overload.
Tempur softens with heat and hardens with cold.
Consequently, the warm human body exerts a perfect effect and optimally adapts its pressure.
Therefore, it is ideal to prevent sores from occurring, but also to improve comfort during sleep.
Viscoelastic foam is not only used in mattresses, but also for medical devices, for example for pillows that are placed under the legs and relieve them, as well as their circulation.
Domestic manufacturers, for example, use Eucatherm C or Twinsaver foam and the like.
More Parents Use People Tracking Devices to Control Their Children
Fear of children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially designed for tracking vehicles, can also follow the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, in case of the disappearance of the nine-year-old girl Anishka Janatkova.
At the moment the device is about the size of a box of cherries, but will soon be reduced to the size of a watch.
Many people were frightened by the case of the missing Anishka and began to report on the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading your privacy.
“We all try to tell ourselves that it is not about spying, but another means of reducing the chances of a tragedy,” says Petr Pilin of the company Macro Weil, one of the providers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they get into someone's bag without their knowledge, but we have not yet come across such cases."
“Most customers actually buy it for safety reasons,” Pilin adds.
In their opinion, children should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bozhkova warns of the fact that if the child does not want to carry it, he will simply throw it away.
“Even the youngest children show great creativity when it comes to intentionally losing certain things if they want to avoid being controlled by them.”
“Parents used to rely heavily on mobile phones, but these could be turned off as easily as the tracking device,” Boková says.
In his opinion, it is debatable whether in case of attack such a device is really useful.
“If it’s a prepared kidnapping, the author will almost always check if the child is carrying any kind of electronic device that can reveal their location.”
“Now it’s the phone.”
"As the use of the tracking devices becomes more widespread, it will also look for them, since their sale will undoubtedly be done with a lot of advertising."
“In such cases, criminals always go one step ahead of the police,” says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the event of an impromptu attack by a pedophile.
According to RC Monitoring’s Robert Cech, who offers tracking services for both vehicles and people, even in the event that the tracking device is destroyed immediately after an attack, his presence can help.
"The device can be configured to send the position regularly after a certain period."
"If it suffers damage, at least it will facilitate the last position of the person in question."
“The more expensive devices have a built-in tilt gauge, so if the person simply slips and sits still, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question,” says Dr. Ech.
In his opinion, such a service can be obtained even with smartphones with navigation, on which only special software should be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that at the moment they are devices with a size similar to a box of matches or smaller mobile phones.
Therefore, they can be lost.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, that’s why tests are currently being done with devices that look like a digital clock.
"In addition, they will have the added advantage that a potential aggressor may not identify the device."
"Or identify him after a while, which can make the police save time," he adds.
Even if the tracking devices are carried on the wrist or hanging, they will still use the same technology used for vehicle tracking.
This is the position check with a GPS system (used in the usual navigation in the car) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
The army has enough wicks to encircle all of Czechia.
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of wick to catch explosives.
Last year, the Ministry of Defense added 224 kilometers of mecha to its arsenal.
Therefore, they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is that the shelf life of the wick is two years, at most four.
The army bought the explosives wick from the STV Group, a. s. for forty million crowns.
The General’s staff responded to MF DNES justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of wick by saying that soldiers need 60 kilometers of wick a year for training maneuvers.
According to the calculations of the army pyrotechnicians, with whom MF DNES was contacted, however, it is decided that, in such a case, such maneuvers should be carried out with frequent use of explosives every year also all generals, senior officers, and even secretaries and cleaners.
They did not want to be exempted either by Defense Minister Alexandr Vondr and Army Captain Vlastimil Picek.
Only in this way could the army be justified in spending 60 kilometers of wick.
This length is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
If so, the army would have sufficient stockpiles for more than ten years.
If on the contrary, as experts say, for the initial training of each new professional comes with a maximum of two meters of wick, the army would have with the new purchase (even adding the consumption of the units of engineers or special) sufficient stocks for the 225 indicated above.
Soldiers of the rapid intervention brigade recently personally complained to Minister Vondra because they say they barely have ammunition for various weapons, so even money-related shooting practices are limited.
And let’s not talk about the lack of underwear.
“I also don’t get to understand that they repeatedly buy us such amounts of wick.”
“But it’s their decision, and they’ll certainly know why they act like that.”
“For us, the military is a good customer that we try to satisfy as a company,” admits STV Group’s commercial director, Jan Däck.
Defense Ministry spokesman Jan Pejchek defends the hundreds of kilometers of mecha by also saying it will have stockpiles of this "munition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan Däck, of STV Group, indicates that the wick only has a shelf life of four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or the police, of two years.
"If stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four," says one of the soldiers who, due to possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
At the end of its life, each munition must be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require additional investment.
Another argument of the Ministry is that, by buying 445 kilometers of mecha, he got a discount.
“They cost us 60 percent less than last year’s order of 244 kilometers,” Pejcek, a spokesman for the Ministry of Defense’s shopping center, said.
Just to compare: the annual wick consumption of the police pyrotechnicians, who remove the munitions from World War II or left by the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 meters for years.
In addition, the police always only ask for the right amount to deplete the ammunition before its shelf life runs out.
They decided for safety reasons for pyrotechnicians and, in the meantime, more modern and reliable wick types can be obtained.
The ministry is already struggling to finish tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the Warsaw Pact era, when the Czechoslovak army of two hundred thousand people was preparing for a campaign on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians MF DNES spoke to, after a couple of years the following problem will occur with the current one: you will have to eliminate hundreds of kilometers of old wick, which is now being bought "cheap".
