A survey that reveals ridiculous norms
The Absurdity Survey of the Year is part of the business tournament for the fourth time.
He has already managed to eliminate some ridiculous rules.
The unknown winner of the new edition of the Absurdity Survey of the Year was the obligation to bring to the administration documents that officials can access online.
The decision was taken by more than a third of the nearly 4,000 voters.
For example, the Social Security Administration requested an extract from the mercantile register, although its officials can obtain it with two mouse movements.
Thanks to the survey, this has changed.
“The Czech Social Security Administration will no longer ask for an extract from the trade register when carrying out a check of the insured’s impositions,” Jana Buraková, a spokeswoman for SSZ, said in a statement.
The objective of the Absurdity of the Year survey is to consult the rules and regulations that companies and entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic must respect and try to eliminate those that are absurd.
For the fourth time this year, he is part of the Hospodăské noviny business tournament, and he is also starting to create a passion among the general public.
While last year’s edition had the participation of 3,000 voters, this year it practically reached 4,000.
And it is not surprising, since we still have several legal obligations that must be respected simply to trade.
“Perhaps in the number of papers needed for the tax return we are in the first place worldwide,” says Karel Havl?ek of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic.
For years, simplification of business rules has been a stated goal of all governments.
However, compared to the rest of the world, the situation improves especially in the Czech Republic.
According to the World Bank, from the point of view of the conditions for owning a company, Czech Republic ranks 74th, i.e. eight places worse than last year.
The Absurdity of the Year contest was held for the first time in 2006 and is repeated every year in the same way.
Anyone can indicate some administrative or bureaucratic nonsense every year between April and the end of September, when the contest closes.
Proposals can be made on the website www.firmaroku.cz. Afterwards, the contest organizer selects seven candidates for the "anti-award" and, during October, allows the public to vote on the Internet through www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and www.ihned.cz.
He wins the nonsense that gets the most votes.
For this year’s survey more than one hundred, in particular 105 rules and regulations that do not make sense, were presented.
The examples were sent by both businessmen and professional associations and journalists.
Among the "finalists" of the competition was the requirement that vehicles for the maintenance of roads and highways pay the toll or that employers with twenty employees, two offices and two bathrooms paint the walls every two years.
The list of this year’s 70 proposals is published on the page of the contest.
The announcement of the competition, which is always held at the beginning of November in Prague’s Wenceslas Square, is part of an event that usually involves personalities from the political and social world.
This year, for example, Eva Svobodová, director of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic, or Petr Kusel, president of the Chamber of Commerce of the Republic, attended this event.
“Economic prosperity cannot be sustained if the state continually hinders entrepreneurs, so my goal is to eliminate every year a minimum of thirty paragraphs that currently unnecessarily complicate trade,” said Martin Kocourek, Minister of Industry and Trade.
Efforts to eliminate absurd regulations are not left in the water of drunkenness.
In 2007, what bothered people the most was the obligation of the employer to communicate three days in advance to the business office of the permanent operating area, intending to go with a position to a fair or exhibition.
This obligation was removed in the new industrial law.
The obligation that finished second in number of votes in 2007, i.e. communication to the labor office by its foreign workers of work trips of up to 30 days, was removed in the law of the so-called green card.
And the third one is won.
The Absurdity of 2009 was the regulation for physiotherapists to have in their consultation a large mirror, a refrigerator and two floor scales.
