Young Czechs get drunk with Fernet and rum. The beer is no longer so, because it works slowly
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
Those are the drinks that cause young drinkers to end up in medical care under the age of 15.
Children who end up lying in the hospital continuously to overcome hangover are no longer an exception.
This stems from the experience of physicians who encounter such cases in hospital pediatric admissions.
"Drinking beer or wine is no longer fashionable, because it takes a long time to get them drunk."
“Fashion is now strong alcoholic beverages,” says the head of paediatrics at Ho?ovice Hospital in central Bohemia, Lud?k Pelikán, to Právo.
"When they manage to get a bottle from their casserole father, it may be whisky, but it's usually Fernet and vodka."
“Vodka has the advantage that it lightens with juice and doesn’t smell so much,” he explains.
This is also confirmed by the spokesperson of the University Hospital Motol, Eva Jurinová.
"Normally, it's usually Fernet or rum."
“These are modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren.”
“In some cases, they use brandy that they picked up at home,” Jurinová adds.
According to Chief Pelikán, 13- and 14-year-old drinkers are usually seen in hospitals.
Prior to Ho?ovice, where he has worked since this year, he worked for a decade in pediatrics in Motol, where ambulances took young people from nearby areas.
“A girl had to come in maybe four times.”
"It began at age 12, when she was brought with 3.5 alcohol in her blood, plus an ecstasy mix," the department's doctor said of the case.
"He was at Holeșovice's fair at some dance party."
“What’s interesting is that his mother wasn’t even surprised that his daughter disappeared for 48 hours,” he said.
It is precisely the lack of interest of parents or even their clear tolerance towards drinking by their children that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that, in the case of children, one cannot speak properly of dependence.
“An alcoholic is a person who has had a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children.”
“In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it is rather due to a systematically failed social or family environment,” explains Chief Pelikán.
According to spokeswoman Jurinová, this year 40 drunk children were hospitalized at the Motol pediatric clinic until mid-November.
However, statistics only show those who come with serious poisoning and should remain in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after the walking medical examination, go home with their parents or with the police, do not count.
In addition to the cases where children simply gather after school and drink brandy, for Pelikán there are three seasonal ups and downs to mention: the day of witches, New Year’s Eve and the end of school.
"In such a circumstance, they drink for the bad grades or, on the contrary, celebrate the beginning of the holiday."
“On Witch’s Day I have seen up to seven drunk children at once in admissions,” adds Pelikán.
Drinkers who spend the night in detox under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hangover at home.
Morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is avoided by injecting a serum with glucose and with the nutrients that are lacking in the body.
"These take it much better, because after the hectic night, they get up well and they don't hurt at all."
“They’re only confused about where they are,” Pelikán says, adding that patients often lose their mood at least when they see the expenses they’ve generated.
Ambulance transfer and hospitalization in a room for serious patients comes to cost tens of thousands of crowns.
“I’ve often used the cost as a means of educating them, when in the visit I tell them directly to the children how much their intoxication has cost and that they would have to spend all summer in a job for young people to earn enough to pay for themselves that night,” adds Pelikán.
Health insurance, in your opinion perhaps as a regressive measure, which usually reimburses people for treatment costs, does not do so in the case of children who drink.
Two L-159 aircraft found for the first time in Spain
Two L-159 aircraft out of a total of five, for which the Czech Ministry of Defense replaced the Casa C-295M aircraft, departed on Tuesday for Seville, where the manufacturer of the Casa - EADS aircraft is located.
