Can civility build a bridge to unite divisions?
After a remarkable campaign of invective and negativity, this week has sparked a bit of civics in Washington.
Is it a harbinger of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no progress on the major issues to be addressed during the upcoming session.
But from what everyone says, it was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two sides, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another empty episode to earn partisan points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the president’s deficit committee was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates members.
That’s just enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are in a trial period, probing each other for signs of cooperativism and commitment, as they try to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
That’s why Tuesday’s meeting and subsequent assessments of it by participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deep-rooted to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, expenses, health care, or social assistance, the two sides are at opposite poles.
However, the November election has softened mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There's no doubt that things have changed with respect to the way things are said," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
“They are inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse party passions, which then become extinct.
That's good."
In some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to widen unemployment subsidies, probably because Republicans can’t make it sound like they’re in favor of tax cuts for the rich, denying the unemployment subsidy for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday’s meeting at the White House, there is greater optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanship when the new 112nd Congress meets in January.
He stated, on the contrary, that it is very likely, even inevitable, that a period of disagreement will begin.
"After the things that have to be done are done, in the short term psychology will turn the situation back into a confrontational one," he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civility can lead to true cooperation.
“I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a rehearsal for the main event of 2012,” he said.
The motives have a lot to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they should try to keep their promises to cut state spending and overturn the new health care law.
Those supportive lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the deficit commission’s recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising some taxes and the retirement age, and cutting spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the toughest jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forcibly put the issue of deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the officials elected on the panel, suggesting that there is, at least at present, little basis or desire for engagement in fiscal matters.
Galston predicts two phases in battles between White House and Congressional Republicans.
The first will take place next year in the form of partisan clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a deadlock, as happened in 1995, then both parties will watch closely the reaction of the people.
Whoever they think is losing will probably change course and seek compromise.
However, this may be an optimistic view.
Partyism and polarization are now larger than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more momentous election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilism shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
