And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of many of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on the three possible solutions to the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, made up of itself, Austria and the Netherlands, among other countries, while the south would leave the currency zone.
The second, the recovery of the framework, although it now seems science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third, a redesign of the euro, in line with German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigor, fines to transgressor countries, possible suspensions of payments from some of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, so now there are no excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government took a constitutional reform out of its sleeve to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany believed should be done (plans of fiscal rigor and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second in the forehead was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully lengthened the decision to save Greece.
Already then it was the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public and published opinion were very much against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel emerges again with a clear position, demanding the reform of the Union treaties, to make it possible to save a country and, at the same time, to force private lenders to run at part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But his proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been approved and, in the coming months, we should attend the process of reform of the Union that makes those measures possible from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And he is telling us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which he may not agree, from that date onwards the old functioning of the euro will be over.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary area, in which infringing countries will be severely sanctioned, may be forced to declare themselves suspended from payments and, in that case, the private sector will also bear part of the cost.
Germany is pointing out to us that we must follow a strict growth path with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge gaps in the balance of payments, such as the one that has presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not tolerate it.
The invitation is clear.
And we would do wrong not to understand it.
It’s not just about bringing the public deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What they demand of us is much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will give way to greater tranquility.
And let us take advantage of the window of opportunity that they have given us, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also understood this and his double manifesto (the reforms promised after last Saturday’s meeting with the big companies and yesterday’s announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite criticism of Merkel, the thesis that order must be put in the house has made its way.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and it doesn’t look like it’s going to move.
And, among the possibilities that are contemplated, the abandonment of a currency zone too crowded with countries that are not serious, cannot be excluded.
Then Germany will always be able to tell us that it had already warned us.
Sport and Law Fraud
Bullshit like that of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but do not want to escape a sanction.
The alleged expulsion by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match against Ajax on 23 November in the Champions League has caused ink rivers to be written about whether or not such behavior is unsportsmanlike and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, in the absence of a few minutes to finish the game (which his team had already clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time when it came to making mistakes to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will end up as leader of their group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction the next match of the league, against Auxerre, and will be able to pass clear of cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA discipline committee has sanctioned the team’s coach, José Mourinho, with two games and with different financial amounts to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the football world.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the rules not written, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the case is due to the fact that it has been starred by a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem boasts of nobility and honor, and which has sometimes fined its players for similar acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his long history of historionic and provocative coach.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behavior not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether with these actions fraud of the law is committed; because, in fact, they are actions respecting the sporting regulation, but seem to evade its meaning.
The issue is to examine the type of harm they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets that comprises the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not endangered, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these assets that is alluded to with fair play is to prevent the team of offending players from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which also did not happen.
Now, the paradoxical thing about the action of Real Madrid players is that it did not accommodate what we normally characterize as cheating or law fraud, since its violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely its action tried to be the most obvious in order to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage offenders gain in the intentional flaws examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that the rival is not put in a disadvantageous situation nor is a profit obtained in the same game, since evidently the result of the action involves leaving the team itself with fewer players.
Nor is it a useful strategy for the next game, as the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, of course, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, since the team can be eliminated at the first of the change, and also with this action the players complete a penalty match and move on to the second card cycle, in which the suspension by accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, from passing rounds, it is not so clear that it is an advantage.
In short, these actions are not against the sporting spirit, of which it is part to make strategic decisions that favor to get the most out of what the rules allow.
In the case before us, the players did not act to evade the application of the penalty (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without escaping the punishment or escaping it.
Although the boundary between ingenuity and law fraud is fuzzy, this time I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, I think, arises from two factors: because it was two self-expulsions and the way in which the transmission of the guideline was carried out to provoke them.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
