China maintains targets to reduce greenhouse gas emissions
The representative of that country at COP16 said that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and detailed that it supports its offer to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020.
China continues to offer to cut its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, the country’s representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP16), Su Wei said his country has made enormous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and re-convert its industry.
In fact, he said, over the past four years his country has invested $245 million in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he made clear that China will not modify its objectives, but will continue to work together with the international community on this matter.
He said China’s climate change strategy is divided into four areas: dialogue; capacity building; institution building and support for pilot programs.
Progress has been made in all these areas, including the adoption last year of a new Energy Law, which includes the objectives set for the reduction of gas emissions, he explained.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, federal authorities have been working in a coordinated way with state and local authorities, to achieve the goals of energy saving, efficient energy use and emission reduction.
In addition, he said, several multi-year plans are underway or have already been completed, both funded by the Chinese government and by governments of other countries.
For example, he said, the Energy Efficient Use Program, which was implemented over the past five years and received investments from the United Nations (UN), government and private initiative.
A provincial climate change project is also underway, another for the change of incandescent foci by savers and one more for mitigation and adaptation, he said.
At the same table, Martin Krol, the country’s government’s scientific advisor on climate change, said China’s efforts have been greater than generally thought.
For example, he said, per capita greenhouse gas emissions in China are six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons; China is responsible for 9 percent of the historical contribution to pollution.
It has also made unprecedented efforts in energy use, such as increasing energy efficiency by 20 percent over the past five years and expects to do just as much by 2020.
