U.S. Changes Rules for Getting a Visa
Individuals will have to go to the Visa Applicant Service Centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and as well as the waiting time.
Starting January 10, 2011, the procedure for processing a visa at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to the Visa Applicant Service Centers (ASCs) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
ASC staff will take the applicant’s biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to arrange the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current fee will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for petition visa cases (including temporary worker visas), and $390 for merchant and investor visas.
Those who wish to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their footprints.
Because the biometric information will be taken at the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed at the Consular Section will stay there for less time than in the past.
Likewise, those who apply for a visa at the Consulates in Ciudad Juarez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the $26 extra service fee.
For additional information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
NASA to find extraterrestrial life
The U.S. space agency has quoted the press to present tomorrow a finding that will make an impact on the search for living beings in space.
The U.S. National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) will unveil an astrobiological discovery tomorrow, Thursday, that could prove the theory that extraterrestrial life does exist.
The finding will be presented at a press conference tomorrow at 1:00 p.m. at NASA headquarters in Washington by experts in astrobiology, science described as tasked with studying the origin, evolution, distribution and future of life in the Universe.
Citing the press, NASA said it would present "a finding that will impact the search for extraterrestrial life," prompting speculation from experts from other countries.
The discovery could demonstrate the theory that creatures exist alongside us and in hostile environments thought to be uninhabitable, and would put on the table the possibility of them becoming intelligent beings like humans if they improve the conditions in which they live.
It appears to be a microbe that was found at the bottom of Mono Lake in Yosemite National Park, California, where it lives in an environment thought to be too poisonous for any form of life, as the lake is rich in arsenic.
Somehow, the creature uses arsenic as a way to survive and this ability increases the possibility that similar life might exist on other planets, which do not have our benevolent atmosphere.
According to astrobiologists, if these organisms use arsenic in their metabolism, it will be shown that “there is another way of life, a second way of life, different from the one we know.”
The space agency will unveil the true scope of the findings at tomorrow’s press conference on Thursday.
The conference will be attended by geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who studies the possibility of life on Mars; and biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists studying Titan (Saturn’s largest moon), under the perspective that its chemistry is similar to that of Earth.
