Partially to blame Dupont
Quebec radio presenter Stéphane Dupont has suffered a setback to the Canadian Broadcasting Standards Council (CCNR) over controversial statements regarding welfare and Haitians, as well as his rude language on the radio.
The CCNR considers that Mr. Dupont and his CHOI 98.1 FM team had the right to express their opinion, but certain statements contained “inaccurate information about social assistance, unduly negative representation of Haitians and rude language that should not be used in broadcasts broadcast during the day.”
The Council has also indicated that debates on suicide, including the disclosure of the names of two persons who had committed suicide, do not violate the broadcasting codes.
The CCNR had received several complaints regarding comments made on broadcasts between 2008 and 2010.
The first decision was issued following a complaint from the Common Front of People Receiving Social Assistance from Quebec.
The group complained that the amounts mentioned in the broadcast were not correct.
Presenters should report reliable and not misleading data.
In connection with suicide, the presenter Stéphane Dupont had stated that suicide was an act of cowardice.
Most Committee members have concluded that the message conveyed was that suicide should not be viewed as a solution to life’s problems.
"The majority of the Committee considers that the episodes in question of 'Dupont le midi' have dealt with a sensitive issue in an equitable and appropriate manner."
Therefore, in this regard, any guilt has been discarded.
The latest litigation referred to the statements made after the Haiti earthquake.
At the time, Stéphane Dupont and Jean-René Dufort had staged a media confrontation that had sparked numerous reactions.
The host of CHOI stated that he had not made any donations to help Haitians because he could not know for sure if those in need would actually receive the money.
The Committee considers that these comments are not abusive, but that their cumulative effect constitutes an unduly negative representation of Haitians.
“I’ve already served my three-day suspension up there.”
“My file has been clean for a year and a half,” the host said.
In all decisions, the Committee denounces the issuance of coarse language.
In any case, radio station CHOI-FM has collaborated “even more than required.”
The consequences will be minimal for the broadcaster, who must, among other things, announce the decisions once in the hours of highest audience within three days.
A Kung Fu King in Montreal
The Algerian-born watchmaker Nacereddine Zemmal has had an extremely peculiar journey.
The athlete, who excels in "sanda" (kung-fu "full contact"), kickboxing and Thai boxing, climbs the world's tatamis and rings in search of new challenges.
“I started practicing martial arts like kung fu and kickboxing 12 years ago in Algeria,” said Zemmal, who has lived in the metropolis since 2008 to advance at the professional level.
“In my case, I look for fights everywhere because, for those who don’t enjoy the on-the-ground game involved in mixed martial arts, there are few competitions in North America.”
The athlete, who works as a security agent and as an employee of UPS, has recently given bad news to his rivals, winning two gold medals in the amateur World Karate and Kickboxing Association (WKA) Championship, held from October 23 to 30 in Edinburgh, Scotland.
“I’ve won in the categories of Kickboxing Full Contact and Thai Boxing,” he explained.
“I am currently preparing to participate in the San Shou World Cup in China.
“They will invite the athletes who have finished in the top four in the last world championship in each category.”
"In 2009, I won the bronze medal in Toronto."
“In 2005, in Vietnam, I finished in eighth place.”
“In 2007, in China, I finished fifth, but I reached third in Toronto in 2009,” he added.
"What's interesting is that I've been making progress in every competition."
“At this point, I’ll be the first one this time or next year!”
San shou or sanda is a discipline native to China in which one is allowed to hit with the fists and feet, as well as throw opponents to the ground.
