Avengers hackers and diligent spies
Wikileaks is of double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandalous in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes on an international scale and envisions a future dominated by regression.
But let’s go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (regardless of which nation it belongs to) is made up exclusively of press clippings.
The “extraordinary” American revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Gaddafi’s sinisterly ridiculous profile has long been giving cabaret artists ideas to create their sketches.
The rule that secret files should only be made up of publicly known news is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not just in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (about the Gral, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) exactly what had been written in previous works.
This is not just because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who engage in occultism do not just rely on what they already know, which reconfirms what they have already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown’s success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little anxiety) the head of the secret services (if he could not be, I know, editor of the Libération), who only considers what he can recognize to be true.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that sent the U.S. embassy in Rome to the State Department was the same as the one published in the Newsweek the week before.
So why have the revelations in these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultured person already knows, that is, that embassies, at least since World War II and since the heads of state can call on the phone or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited representation exercises, have become centers of espionage.
Any viewer who watches investigative films knows this perfectly, we only seem to know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that an ordinary hacker can look up the secrets of the most powerful country in the world greatly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the "judges".
But let us enter into the true nature of what has happened.
Formerly, in Orwell’s time, he could conceive himself to all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy has come true since, being able to control every move thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it is now, that not even the crypts of the secrets of power can escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer keep its own secrets stand?
It is true, as Georg Simmel said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets means taking away all power from her.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and a lot to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any confidential information on the network, since it would be like publishing it on a poster in the street.
But it’s also clear that with current technologies, you can’t expect to have confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state has traveled by plane and contacted one of the counterparts.
How will they be able to maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my foresight is a science fiction thing and, therefore, novelistic, but I imagine government agents moving discreetly in diligence with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, at most, hiding some data written on the heels of their shoes.
That information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked drawers: after all, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is currently advancing like a crab, i.e. backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a telegraph with cables (telephones).
The (analog) videotapes had allowed the film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, uncovering all the secrets of the montage, while now the (digital) CDs only allow you to move forward or backward from chapter to chapter, that is, to enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the displacements that entails, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary for politics and communication techniques to take us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was secretly going on in the embassies.
Currently, it is the embassies that ask for confidential information from the press.
Climate: France’s shambles in its funding pledges
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unlocked funding promises (called fast start or early) made by developed countries have been fulfilled.
And the french fries have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged to contribute €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (i.e. €420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put on the table its best letters to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its member states, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation proved appreciable and was appreciated for what it was really worth: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Accord, the money must be “new and additional” to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without harming official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what “new and additional” means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as a reference year: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added over three years in terms of fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references with respect to the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers the financing of "all new projects" of 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to expenditure in previous years or the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of France’s aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while pretending to respect its commitment to “new and additional” funds.
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses the method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider each euro borrowed to be equivalent to one euro donated.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the reduction of emissions that are based on more effective technologies), it is false to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated ... At most, only the cost of the loan for the country that grants the loan (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be calculated for its commitments.
But France does not find such reasoning useful: it “respects” its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros); refer to the EU document to see it for your own eyes.
It is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to fulfill its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
That's a good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France performs a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending just 36.1 million euros, he manages to give the impression that he spends 420 million “new and additional”, as he had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has dealt with the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why were the other Member States going to continue to donate when they could just lend?) and in the negotiations, since developing countries are not fools...
The chapter on early financing is a meticulous, relatively short-term, in relation to all climate negotiations.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it doesn't.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, especially, France could move forward the debates on gambling in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter that is currently being debated): we will not get rid of the question of "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its stance to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additional character" and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move the negotiations forward.
