A 10-year-old boy ingests 81 different chemicals in one day, according to a study published Wednesday by the Générations Futures association (the old movement for the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have significant statistical value considering the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem addressed", acquired in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September the foods that usually consume a child of about ten years in four meals and a snack a day.
These meals taken as a model, which comply with official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three parts of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day), as well as treats, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances are classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EPs), according to studies from various institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
“Although, in virtually all cases, the legal limits for each of the chemicals are not exceeded individually, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic contaminants and/or PE is worrisome.”
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that can damage the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a school snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans, included in the food, in which the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian steak, canned tuna and even bread bar or gum were dressed with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyses found the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the slice of salmon was the most “nutritive” with 34 chemical residues detected and even analysis of the plastic dish used to heat food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The ultimate risk these “pollutant cocktails” generate for the consumer is “probably underestimated,” the study says.
